Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel just needs a bindable property:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

**3. Bind the Editor in your XAML:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **Stopped** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **Destroying** | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |
| Don't save in **Deactivated** | That fires for dialogs/notification shade — too aggressive |
| Use `Preferences` | Fast and synchronous; avoid DB writes in lifecycle handlers |
| **Resumed ≠ first launch** | `Resumed` only fires after `Stopped`, not on initial launch |

Keep handlers under ~1–2 seconds to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS.
